  "slug": "christmas-cake",
  "title": "Christmas cake",
  "subtitle": "Aged fruit cake fed with brandy over several weeks",
  "excerpt": "A rich, dark fruit cake baked in late autumn and fed weekly with brandy until Christmas. The long storage develops flavour the fresh-baked version cannot achieve: the fruitcake tightens, deepens, and rewards patience.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: the rich fruit cake recipe with the method of feeding with spirits. Eliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845), Project Gutenberg: the overnight fruit soak. Florence White, Good Things in England (1932): regional feeding conventions. The Christmas fruitcake tradition in Britain dates to the 17th century, replacing the Twelfth Night cake after the tradition shifted to Christmas Day.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The Christmas cake is a long project, not an afternoon's baking. Bake it in October or November; the weeks of ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "feeding the cake",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "feeding the cake",
                  "termId": "cmpbjxdc60000n8v4jlet02ot"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " with brandy are what make it a Christmas cake rather than a fruit cake. The flavour cannot be rushed or imitated by a last-minute soak.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "style": "tip"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "text": "Line the tin thoroughly: a double layer of baking paper on the base and sides, with an extra strip around the outside of the tin tied with string. Four hours at low heat is a long time and the paper insulates the cake from the direct heat of the tin.",
                "type": "text"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
