        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The night before: soak the fruit",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine all the dried fruit and peel in a large bowl, pour over the brandy, stir, and cover with cling film. Leave overnight or for at least 8 hours.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the tin",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 150°C conventional. Line a 23 cm round tin with a double layer of baking paper on the base and a double layer on the sides extending 5 cm above the rim. Wrap a double layer of brown paper or baking paper around the outside of the tin and secure with string. This insulates the cake.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the batter and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beat the butter and sugar together until combined (it will not go pale and fluffy with muscovado sugar; that is normal). Beat in the eggs one at a time. Fold in the flour, baking powder, spices, and ground almonds. Stir in the treacle and citrus zests. Add the soaked fruit and chopped almonds and fold to combine evenly. Transfer to the prepared tin and level the surface, making a slight hollow in the centre so the top bakes flat. Bake for 3 hours 45 minutes to 4 hours. After 2 hours, check the top; if it is browning too quickly, lay a loose sheet of foil over it. The cake is done when a skewer comes out clean and the surface feels firm when you press the centre.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "First feed and storage",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "While the cake is still warm, prick the top and base all over with a skewer and spoon 2 tablespoons of brandy over the surface. Leave to cool completely in the tin. Once cold, wrap the cake tightly in a double layer of baking paper and then foil, and store in a tin. Feed weekly until the week before Christmas: prick, spoon over 2 tablespoons of spirit, rewrap. Apply marzipan and icing in the final week.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
